sec.p:
In SAR operations, the GF is utilized to enhance images before recognizing and classifying objects. This linear filter uses the Gaussian function to apply weighted values to each pixel, which results in smooth refinement and noise reduction. It is more effective in removing generally dispersed noise, which is crucial for improving the quality of aerial and thermal images used in rescue operations. The GF employs a kernel center to maintain important characteristics while removing distortions. The values of each factor in the Gaussian smoothing filter can be calculated numerically utilizing the Gaussian function in (1).
\begin{equation*}
g(y, x)=\frac{1}{d} f \frac{y^{2}+x^{2}}{2 \sigma^{2}}
\tag{1}
\end{equation*}
Where $\sigma$ denote the SE (standard deviation) of the Gaussian kernel, and $d$ is the normalization invariable, which assure accurate weighting of pixel intensities.

The Vision Transformer (ViT) improves SAR by identifying individuality in aerial and sensor images. It breaks images into patches, embeds, and uses (Multi-head Self-Attention) and a Feed Forward Network, as in (2):
\begin{equation*}
\operatorname{Attention}\left(R_{j}, L_{j}, U_{j}\right)=\operatorname{Softmax}\left(\frac{R L^{S}}{\sqrt{c}}\right) U \tag{2}
\end{equation*}

Self-attention is calculated as (3):
\begin{equation*}
\operatorname{MSA}(R, L, U) = [\text{Attention} \left(R_{1}, L_{1}, U_{1}\right); \ldots. ; \text{Attention} \left.\left(R_{S}, L_{S}, U_{S}\right)\right] X_{P} \tag{3}
\end{equation*}

The attention mechanism originated from research into human visual perception and was initially applied to machine translation. It has gained widespread use across various DL applications, including SAR operations, along with image and audio identification. In SAR tasks, various features contribute irregularly to identifying individuals in danger highly complex due to environmental challenges, object variability, and small-sized targets. The attention mechanism directs computational resources toward critical aspects, such as locating survivors, detecting hazards, and assessing terrain circumstances, while filtering out less relevant information to enhance effectiveness and accuracy. n SAR missions, various features such as object size, movement, water turbulence, and lighting conditions contribute irregularly to the detection process. The attention mechanism dynamically prioritizes essential features, such as survivors' locations, potential hazards, and environmental conditions, while suppressing less relevant background noise. This results in better identification of distress signals, improved situational awareness, and more accurate classification of floating objects in aerial surveillance footage. The general numerical demonstration of the attention device is given in (4):
\begin{equation*}
P=\operatorname{Softmax}\left(R L^{S}\right) \cdot U
\tag{4}
\end{equation*}

GANs have two primary elements: a generator and a discriminator. In SAR missions, the generator can recreate scenarios of disaster, restore images of missing persons, or enhance aerial surveillance images captured at low resolutions, while the discriminator verifies the results produced as realistic. The generator aims to approximate the distribution of real data, denoted as $O_{\text {data }}$, while it's learned distribution is represented as $O_{H}(w; \theta)$, where $\theta$ denotes the model parameters. The objective is to optimize $\theta$ such that $O_{H}(w; \theta)$) closely resembles $\int_{W} O_{\text {data }}(w)$, as in (5). This approach significantly enhances the identification of survivors and floating objects in drone imagery, optimizing mission-critical decision-making by adversarial training.
\begin{align*}
& \quad \theta^{*}=\underset{\theta}{\operatorname{argmax}} \prod_{j=1} O_{H}\left(w^{i}; \theta\right) \\
& =\underset{\theta}{\operatorname{argmaxlog}} \prod_{j=1} O_{H}\left(w^{i}; \theta\right) \\
& =\underset{\theta}{\operatorname{argmax}} \sum_{j=1}^{n} \log O_{H}\left(w^{j}; \theta\right)\left\{w^{1}, w^{2}, \ldots, w^{n}\right\} \operatorname{fromO}_{\text {data }}(w) \\
& \approx \underset{\theta}{\operatorname{argmax} F_{w \sim O_{\text {data }}}\left[\log O_{H}(w; \theta)\right]} \\
& =\underset{\theta}{\operatorname{argmax}} \underset{\int_{W}}{\int_{W} O_{\text {data }}(w) \log O_{H}(w; \theta) c w-} \tag{5}
\end{align*}

During SAR operations, the process reduces the gap between real world aerial images from the AFO dataset and the output from the generator such that synthetic data closely matches actual rescue conditions. This enables synthetic training datasets to be created in order to enhance the model's generalization in various maritime scenarios.. In SAR missions, this can be framed as minimizing the divergence between the real data distribution $\int_{W} O_{\text {data }}(w)$ and the generator's distribution $O_{H}(w; \theta)$. The goal is to optimize $\theta$ so that the generated data closely resembles real-world rescue scenarios, such as terrain maps, survivor locations, or distress signal patterns (6).
\begin{gather*}
\operatorname{minmax} U(C, H) \\
=\mathrm{F}_{w \sim o_{\text {data }}}(w)[\log C(w)]+F_{y \sim o_{y}(y)}[\log (1-C(H(z)))] \tag{6}
\end{gather*}

Two fundamental strategies are presented to improve WSOA's efficacy in SAR missions. The first strategy is based on the OBL (Opposition-Based Learning) method, which increases solution diversity by treating each candidate as a pair of complimentary answers. This technique increases the algorithm's examination ability, guaranteeing efficient path planning and coverage during SAR missions. The resistance-based equations are stated as (7) and (8):
\begin{gather*}
Y_{x, \text { male }}^{\text {new }}=Y_{x, \text { male }}^{\max }+Y_{x, \text { male }}^{\min }-Y_{x, \text { male }} \tag{7}\\
Y_{x, \text { female }}^{\text {new }}=Y_{x, \text { female }}^{\max }+Y_{x, \text { female }}^{\min }-Y_{x, \text { female }} \tag{8}
\end{gather*}

Another enhancement to WS for SAR missions involves the integration of chaos theory, which replaces completely random variables with quasi-random counterparts. This refinement accelerates convergence and enhances efficiency. To generate chaotic variables, a sinusoidal map is employed, as represented in (9):
\begin{equation*}
\mathrm{q}(\mathrm{i}+1)=O. q^{2}(i) \times \sin (\pi. q(i))
\tag{9}
\end{equation*}
